properties.sex: Information on the data source, the historical availability, definitions of the terms used, and the geographies available can be found at http://www.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/4105-eng.htm. For questions and comments, contact income@statcan.gc.ca, Income Statistics Division, Client Services, Jean Talon Building, 5th Floor, Ottawa, Ontario K1A 0T6.
Taxfilers are people who filed a tax return for the reference year and were alive at the end of the year.
Dependent is a member of a family who did not file a personal income tax return for the referenced year.
Federal income tax is the amount of income tax that a taxfiler is required to pay to the Federal Government of Canada.

Provincial income tax is the amount of income tax that a taxfiler is required to pay to the government of the province of residence (as of December 31 of the reference year), or to the government of another province where the taxfiler is operating a business with a permanent establishment.

Definitions of Employment Insurance premiums, Canada Pension Plan (CPP) and Quebec Pension Plan (QPP) premiums, registered pension plan premiums and annual union, professional or like dues are available from the User's Guide to this series, available at http://www.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/4105-eng.htm.

Definitions of Employment Insurance benefits, Canada Pension Plan (CPP) and Quebec Pension Plan (QPP) are available from the User's Guide to this series, available at http://www.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/4105-eng.htm.

Total income is income from all sources. A detailed definition of what is included in total income is available from the User's Guide to this series, available at http://www.statcan.gc.ca/imdb-bmdi/4105-eng.htm.

The census metropolitan area (CMA) of Ottawa-Gatineau straddles the provincial borders of Ontario and Quebec. Three census agglomerations (CA) also straddle provincial borders: Campbellton straddles New Brunswick and Quebec, Hawkesbury straddles Ontario and Quebec, and Lloydminster straddles Alberta and Saskatchewan. Data for the combined provincial parts are provided at the end of the list of CMAs and CAs. Prior to 2008, data for the two parts of the Ottawa-Gatineau CMA may be added together to provide a total for the area, with the exception of medians, percentages, indexes and averages.
